      {
        "id": 2216268,
        "name": "Tom Reddick",
        "username": "Tom_Reddick",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/t/ecb155/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2017-07-10T04:48:06.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>2014 was definitely painful on the pricing front. In Ramonet\u2019s defense, the price increases took him up to the same price points of his peers (many of which have worse premox histories)- but for Bienvenue and Batard that translated into an increase of about 65%. Chevalier and Montrachet about 15%. Looking at 2015 premier cru pricing in Europe- and the short crop in 2016- for now it seems up is the only trend to expect.</p>\n<p>For my part, I turned 44 today and I have about 350 bottles in my cellar- all damn good ones selected based on 22 years of tasting experience. Around age 70, I expect I will free myself of any remaining wine plus a number of other non-essential possessions as my father and grandfather did. Growing up, I thought they were crazy- but I get it now as I get closer to that time in my life. And given that I only have nice wine a few times a year (not much different than before- but on a less grand scale at each tasting), I have most of what I need now. I do not see the cellar getting above 500 bottles ever again- and even that would only be near term if we have another string of vintages I really like.</p>\n<p>Ramonet is one of the very few producers I want to grow old with- and that makes the cost easier to bear for the few additional vintages I need to fill out the cellar.</p>",
